          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822227?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Twitter 的鸟标志装饰着该公司位于旧金山的总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：constanza hevia/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001078088"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/collin-eaton" itemprop="url" rel="author">科林·伊顿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 23 日上午 8:52 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>埃隆·马斯克表示，Twitter 将很快改变其品牌，并在周日早些时候发布的一系列推文中表示，该社交媒体平台将把其长期使用的蓝鸟标志改为“X”。</p><p> “如果今晚发布了一个足够好的 X 标志，我们明天就会让它在全球范围内上线，”马斯克写道。这位推特的亿万富翁所有者还发布了一张闪烁的“X”的图片。</p><p> “很快我们就会告别 Twitter 品牌，并逐渐告别所有的鸟类，”马斯克在另一篇文章中写道。在同一系列推文中，马斯克发起了一项关于将默认平台颜色更改为黑色的用户民意调查。</p><p>推特没有立即回应置评请求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822228?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Twitter 的亿万富翁埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 与字母 X 有着悠久的历史。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的马修·布希</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Twitter 在今年早些时候的一份法律文件中表示，它有一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-inc-changes-its-name-to-x-corp-and-moves-to-nevada-703ac892?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新的公司名称</a>X Corp.，是一家在内华达州注册成立的私人控股公司，而不是 Twitter 之前的注册地特拉华州。 Twitter 的主要业务地点仍然是公司总部所在地旧金山。文件显示，X Corp. 的母公司名为 X Holdings Corp.。</p><p>网上议论纷纷猜测，公司更名是<a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1577428272056389633?" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">马斯克在推特上发布的宏伟愿景</a>的一部分，即利用他对 Twitter 的收购来帮助创建“X，一切应用程序”。</p><p>马斯克的火箭公司太空探索技术公司被称为 SpaceX，他与这封信有着悠久的历史。他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-revives-old-banking-dream-in-pursuing-250-billion-twitter-valuation-88289aba?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">以前的在线银行初创公司</a>X.com 后来与另一家公司合并后成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PYPL" class="company-name">PayPal</a> 。马斯克经常称他的一个孩子为“X”。</p><p> “不确定是什么微妙的线索泄露了它，但我喜欢字母 X，”马斯克周日发推文，并附上了一张自己用前臂画出 X 的照片。</p><p>写信给 Collin Eaton <a href="mailto:collin.eaton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">collin.eaton@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 12:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349<author><![CDATA[Collin Eaton]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>铁路交通</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>铁路客运</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>贝宝控股</category><category>PYPL</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>铁路交通</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>铁路客运</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[At Startup That Says Its AI Writes Medical Records, Humans Do a Lot of the Work]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> DeepScribe 拥有一支团队来纠正术语、删除错误处方并添加帐单代码<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-801306/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图：Emil Lendof/WSJ； iStock<span>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/WSJ 提供；股票</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067317"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067317"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joseph-walker" itemprop="url" rel="author">约瑟夫·沃克</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 23 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-startup-that-says-its-ai-writes-medical-records-humans-do-a-lot-of-the-work-794be22e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>美国各地数百名医生已将他们与患者的私人谈话录音委托给一家初创公司，该公司承诺<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/businesses-seek-out-chatgpt-tech-for-searching-and-analyzing-their-own-data-393ef4fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过人工智能</a>将谈话内容转化为可用的医疗记录。</p><p>据现任和前任工作人员称，该技术在生成报告时犯了多个错误，例如未能使用正确的医学术语以及添加了患者未服用的药物。</p><p>健康科技初创公司 DeepScribe 的创始人表示，为了修复这些错误，该公司依靠 200 名承包商来监听医疗对话并修改记录。工作人员还使用谷歌搜索来查找帐单代码。</p><p>医疗保健因其所有管理任务、数据输入和文书工作而成为人工智能的成熟目标。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong> DeepScribe 对其人工智能的力量做出了全面的宣称，但其承包商所做的关键工作表明，如果没有大量的人工协助，该技术仍然无法完成医学上的一些基本任务。</p><p> DeepScribe 联合创始人 Matthew Ko 和 Akilesh Bapu 表示，诸如列出患者未服用的药物等错误在许多人工智能算法中很常见，这些算法经常会产生“幻觉”，将虚假信息呈现为真实信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="427" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-801249?width=639&amp;height=427" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Akilesh Bapu（左）和 Matthew Ko 于 2017 年共同创立了 DeepScribe。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国商业资讯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>创始人表示，DeepScribe 的软件能够写入每条记录的 80%，但该公司雇佣了 200 名员工，“捕捉人工智能等新兴技术可能产生的错误，让医疗保健提供者有信心知道他们的笔记是由我们团队的培训成员审核的，以保证准确性。”</p><p> Ko 和 Bapu 表示，让人类审查人工智能的工作并识别其错误有助于训练算法并提高其准确性。他们表示，DeepScribe 在其网站和销售演示中披露了质量保证工作。</p><p>医生有责任确保添加到患者医疗记录中的报告的准确性。 DeepScribe 现任和前任员工表示，他们不知道医生未能发现任何通过人工审查的错误。</p><p>以下对 DeepScribe 及其技术和人类员工使用情况的描述基于对现任和前任员工的采访，以及对 DeepScribe 员工之间的沟通和其他公司材料的审查。</p><p>公司工作很繁琐<strong>&nbsp;</strong>但医疗保健的关键环节：记录保存。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="539" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-808576?width=700&amp;height=539" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DeepScribe 在其网站上描述了如何利用人工智能来填写电子健康记录。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>医生将他们的谈话记录记录到患者的医疗记录中。医生和其他护理人员可以稍后查看摘要，以快速了解患者的病史并帮助为治疗提供信息。健康保险公司利用这些记录来确定向医生支付的服务费用。</p><p>但把聊天记录写下来<strong>&nbsp;</strong>整理成连贯的笔记是一项耗时的工作。为了节省时间，许多医生只是复制并粘贴患者上次就诊时输入的注释，然后根据需要进行调整。一些医生会使用语音识别软件口述患者报告，或者让工作人员陪同他们探访患者并做笔记。</p><p> DeepScribe 对其自动化记录保存技术的力量做出了大胆承诺，称它将“改写医疗记录的制作方式”。</p><p>该公司表示，它不仅仅是抄写医生就诊的记录。它的人工智能会逐字记录每次对话的文字记录（总计可达数千字），并将其转换成标准化报告，并可合并到患者的电子病历中。</p><p> DeepScribe 提供了其销售演示和网站常见问题解答部分的图像，其中包括质量保证团队审查人工智能生成的报告的准确性的披露。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="500" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-808575?width=700&amp;height=500" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">员工使用 DeepScribe Slack 频道寻求有关人工智能在笔记中添加额外药物名称等问题的建议。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>然而，该网站的大部分内容都强调其“人工智能驱动”技术的好处。该公司在网站上表示，与旧服务相比，该软件“更准确”且“更少的手动操作”。 “人工智能正在彻底改变几乎每个行业。现在，轮到医疗保健了，”该网站称。</p><p>医疗保健支出占美国 GDP 的近五分之一，使其成为最热门、最有利润潜力的市场之一<strong>&nbsp;</strong>对于人工智能<strong>。</strong>数据分析提供商 PitchBook 的数据显示，由于商业潜力，从 2018 年到 2022 年，风险投资家向专注于医疗保健的人工智能公司投资了 173 亿美元。</p><p>然而，哈佛医学院生物医学信息学教授兼主席艾萨克·科哈内 (Isaac Kohane) 博士表示，对于许多健康技术初创公司来说，他们对技术的承诺与实际交付的产品之间存在巨大差距。</p><p> “泡沫如此之大，以至于有太多的资金追逐太少的好公司，”他说。</p><p>据 PitchBook 称，总部位于旧金山的 DeepScribe 成立于 2017 年，已筹集 3730 万美元的风险投资融资，在 2021 年 12 月上次融资后估值为 1.8 亿美元。</p><p> Ko 和 Bapu 表示，该公司约有 1,000 名医生和其他医疗保健提供者使用其服务。他们表示，该公司的收入有望大幅超过 650 万美元<strong>&nbsp;</strong>今年。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>创始人表示，其他人工智能医生的竞争对手每月收取的医疗费用为 2,000 至 3,000 美元，该公司的收费仅为六分之一至八分之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="581" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-808574?width=639&amp;height=581" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名员工在 DeepScribe Slack 频道上进行了调查，寻求有关术语的建议。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>借助 DeepScribe 的产品，医生可以使用该公司开发的智能手机应用程序记录每次患者就诊的情况，然后将记录上传到 DeepScribe 的数据库中。</p><p> Ko 和 Bapu 表示，DeepScribe 使用其他公司的软件来生成音频转录。然后 DeepScribe 的人工智能开始总结记录，并将其放入患者的医疗记录中。</p><p>人工智能分析记录并突出显示医学相关信息，例如患者的病史和当前症状，以及医生的后续计划。人工智能将突出显示的信息写成完整的句子。</p><p> DeepScribe 的人类工作人员（内部称为抄写员）审查录音并将其与文字记录和人工智能生成的句子进行比较。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，问题始于笔录。它们通常包含脱节、无意义的句子。</p><p> DeepScribe 表示其软件还<strong>&nbsp;</strong>建议将关键数据包含在患者的医疗记录中，包括计费保险代码。</p><p>工作人员表示，文字记录和人工智能生成的摘要有时也会错误地拼写药物名称。例如，其中一位知情人士称，一份记录将一名患者自称正在服用的治疗偏头痛的药物称为“Shelby”，而该患者实际上使用的是 Ubrelvy 品牌。</p><p> DeepScribe 软件有时会建议对转录本中拼写正确的药物进行更改。例如，有人说，它建议将抗抑郁药 Remeron 的名称改为 Remora（一种鱼），或者提议使用 Toreador（西班牙语中斗牛士的意思）来代替止痛药 Toradol。</p><p> “还有其他人注意到人工智能有时会添加额外的药物吗？”一名审查人工智能工作的员工在 2022 年 11 月发给同事的 Slack 消息中写道，《华尔街日报》对该消息进行了评论。 “我已经多次看到不同药物的情况，所以很好奇。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为人工智能在医学领域的最大前景和风险是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，他们经常不得不进行修正并填补人工智能留下的其他空白。他们说，每份医疗报告的大部分内容都是他们撰写的。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》对抄写员使用的 Slack 频道上的消息进行了审查，发现他们正在寻求一系列问题的答案。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>讨论的主题包括是否<strong>&nbsp;</strong>描述一位未透露姓名的患者，他向医生抱怨睡眠不好，患有鼻窦充血或失眠。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》看到的 Slack 消息显示，DeepScribe 的人工智能常常无法用医学术语取代患者所说的口语。该公司希望其人类员工能够履行这一职能。</p><p> “有没有关于肚脐的医学术语，哈哈，”一位抄写员问道。 “脐！” DeepScribe 管理员做出了回应。 “或者谷歌也告诉我‘脐’。”</p><p>一名员工表示，在公司开始使用新版本的人工智能软件后，过去几个月的笔录和报告质量有所提高。</p><p> Ko和Bapu表示，该算法还可以学习每位医生的谈话和写作风格，并提高其准确性。员工表示，他们负责使笔记符合医生的喜好，这些喜好由医生传达给 DeepScribe 的销售人员。</p><p> DeepScribe 表示，其人工智能构建了大部分报告，其人类工作人员扫描笔录和报告<em>&nbsp;</em>获取人工智能可能遗漏的任何信息。 Ko 和 Bapu 表示，工作人员将人工智能工作的准确性提高了 15 个百分点，达到 95%，剩下的 5% 是由医生在接受纸条之前校对纸条完成的。 《华尔街日报》联系的使用 DeepScribe 软件的医生没有回应采访请求。</p><p>抄写员还负责选择用于识别每位患者的诊断、症状和程序的账单代码，因为 DeepScribe 的人工智能<strong>&nbsp;</strong>现任和前任员工表示，无法检索代码。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="385" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-808573?width=700&amp;height=385" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DeepScribe Slack 频道的员工众包了关于在笔记中包含哪些医疗账单代码的建议。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>为了进行编码，许多大型医疗机构和医院聘请了通过证书或副学士学位课程完成医疗编码培训的专业人员。 DeepScribe 对抄写员的培训很少，包括指定<strong>&nbsp;</strong>一名工作人员表示，常用代码的使用以及如何在互联网上搜索其他代码。知情人士称，经理指示抄写员使用谷歌查找诊断代码（ICD-10）。</p><p>今年早些时候，一位抄写员在 Slack 上询问应该使用哪个 ICD-10 代码来治疗膝关节炎，但他不知道属于哪种关节炎或哪个膝盖。一位经理回复了搜索词“关节炎未指定的膝关节 ICD 10”的 Google 结果页面的屏幕截图。</p><p> DeepScribe 表示，它为抄写员提供 ICD-10 培训，并且只向医生推荐这些代码，由医生负责确认其准确性。</p><p>现任和前任工作人员表示，一些医生和患者似乎没有意识到人类正在收听这些录音。据工作人员称，在一些录音中，医生告诉患者他们的就诊正在被记录，但将完全由人工智能进行分析，没有人会听。</p><p> DeepScribe 的工作人员表示，在谈话过程中，患者与医生分享了一些私密的细节，包括药物滥用案例和家庭问题。知情人士说，成绩单通常包括患者的全名和医生执业名称的缩写。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EC817295-03D0-4031-B40B-694D7BDE2797&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fat-startup-that-says-its-ai-writes-medical-records-humans-do-a-lot-of-the-work-794be22e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">新的人工智能语音和视频工具看起来和听起来都像你。但它们能骗过你的家人或银行吗？ 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 当天用她的人工智能双胞胎代替了自己，以找出答案。图片插图：埃琳娜·斯科蒂<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>法律专家表示，根据联邦健康保险流通和责任法案 (HIPAA)，DeepScribe 及其员工可以查看患者的医疗信息，但他们有义务保护数据的机密性。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，他们在联邦 HIPAA 法和健康隐私方面接受的培训很少。</p><p>法律专家表示，HIPAA 并不要求医生告诉患者其他人可以检查他们的数据，包括他们的就诊记录。</p><p>然而，科技公司健康隐私顾问乔伊·普里茨 (Joy Pritts) 表示，即使合法，出于道德原因，医生也应该告诉患者，他们的谈话正在被记录并与第三方公司及其员工共享。</p><p> “他们歪曲了他们对病人所做的事情，并以某种方式让病人对他们所说的话感到更舒服和更自由，”普里茨说。</p><p> DeepScribe 表示，所有员工都完成了 17 个步骤的培训计划，其中包括 HIPAA 合规性。</p><p>写信给约瑟夫·沃克： <a href="mailto:joseph.walker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joseph.walker@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-startup-that-says-its-ai-writes-medical-records- humans-do-a-lot-of-the-work-794be22e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-startup-that-says-its-ai-writes-medical-records- humans-do-a-lot-of-the-work-794be22e<author><![CDATA[Joseph Walker]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Retirement Tax Break That Ends the Fear of Outliving Your 401(k)]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>退休时用积蓄购买特殊长寿年金的利与弊<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074128"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822001?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">图片插图：Ericka Burchett/《华尔街日报》 </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074128"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">通过<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ashlea-ebeling" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿什莉·埃贝林</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 23 日上午 12:03（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-break-qlac-annuity-contract-ee88fe4c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>数以百万计的美国人有充分的理由担心他们的退休储蓄会花光。鲜为人知的税收优惠年金可以帮助避免这种情况，为生命的最后几年提供有保障的收入。</p><p>从今年开始，美国人可以使用最多 20 万美元的退休账户购买合格的长寿年金合同 (QLAC)。国会设定的新缴款限额高于 145,000 美元或余额的 25%，以较低者为准。</p><p>年金是一种保险合同，您可以购买它来提供像养老金一样的稳定收入，从而更容易规划预期寿命的不确定性。 QLAC 已经存在了十年，比典型的即期年金提供更多的终生收入，因为付款直到晚年（例如 80 或 85 岁）才开始。它们还享有特殊的税收优惠。</p><p>从养老金保障转向依赖 401(k) 计划，工人变成了投资者和精算师，他们的任务是建立足够多的储备金以维持其一生。 QLAC 是消除一些猜测的一种方法。</p><p> “更多的人应该能够利用这一点，”2014 年帮助创建 QLAC 的前财政部顾问 Mark Iwry 说道。</p><p>减少退休储蓄余额可以减少退休人员从 73 岁起必须提取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/reducing-the-pain-from-required-retirement-withdrawals-this-year-11665098435?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的应税提款</a>金额。</p><p> QLAC 的缺点是前期成本较高，如果发生紧急情况并且您在开始付款之前需要资金，您就无法动用它。它是锁定的。支付的金额还取决于您的寿命。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="699" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821802?width=700&amp;height=699" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">查理·沃克 (Charlie Walker) 和格洛丽亚·沃克 (Gloria Walker) 指望一份合格的长寿年金合同能够为 85 岁后的生活提供保障。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：沃克家族</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>新泽西州巴斯金里奇的查理·沃克 (Charlie Walker) 获得了 QLAC，以帮助减少年度分配中的税收，并确保他的妻子格洛丽亚 (Gloria) 可以部分替代他的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="company-name">AT&amp;T</a>养老金，如果他先去世，这笔养老金只能持续到他的一生。 “我们认为她会比我活得更久，”沃克说道，并指出他妻子的祖母都活到了 90 多岁。</p><p>去年12月，当他79岁和她76岁时，他们用他个人退休账户中的钱购买了一张价值108,000美元的QLAC，并选择了终身继续支付的选项。每年近 16,000 美元的支出从他 85 岁时开始。在接下来的几年里，他将避免从 IRA 获得超过 20,000 美元的应税分配。</p><p>他们选择了较低的死亡抚恤金。如果他们在赔付额达到 108,000 美元之前双双去世，则他们的四个女儿将获得差额。</p><h3>长寿年金如何运作</h3><p>通过 QLAC，储户在即将退休时（例如 65 岁时）将退休金账户中的钱交给保险公司。反过来，保险公司将同意从未来一两年开始，每年向您支付一笔固定的终生金额。</p><p>据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MET" class="">大都会人寿</a>称，一名 65 岁的老人可以购买价值 20 万美元的 QLAC，无需死亡抚恤金，85 岁时每月可支付 11,175 美元<span class="company-name-type">。</span>第一年的支出为 134,100 美元。一个 75 岁的老人每月只能拿到 7,000 多美元，第一年大约是 84,000 美元。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您如何将 QLAC 纳入您的退休计划？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>在最简单的 QLAC 版本中，当您或配偶去世时，赔付就会停止，保险公司会保留剩余的钱。大多数合同都有死亡抚恤金条款，允许继承人收回购买价格减去任何支出。</p><p>大都会人寿表示，在年金中加入死亡抚恤金后，65 岁老人的每月支出将减少至约 8,700 美元，75 岁老人的每月支出将减少至 5,200 美元。延期时间越长，支付的金额就越大。</p><p>伊沃里说，你付钱是为了确保自己不会用完退休储蓄。</p><p> QLAC 的年度支出算作应税收入，但有一些税收优惠。由于存入年金的资金不再存在于退休账户中，因此当要求的最低分配额从 73 岁开始时，退休人员不需要每年从储蓄中提取那么多资金。如果您有一个 100 万美元的退休账户并购买了 200,000 美元的 QLAC，您的 RMD 将基于 800,000 美元的余额。</p><h3>哪里可以购买 QLAC</h3><p>获得 QLAC 的两种方法是通过您的公司退休计划（当有选择时），或者通过财务规划师、保险代理人或经纪公司在个人市场上获得。例如，富达 (Fidelity) 通过由五家保险公司组成的市场直接向拥有 IRA 的投资者提供此类服务。</p><p> QLAC 仍然是一种小众保险产品。 2022 年销售额为 2.34 亿美元，但此选项的市场要大得多。根据投资公司协会的数据，美国人的退休账户有 22.3 万亿美元。</p><p>顾问表示，人们在规划未来时往往会低估自己的寿命。根据精算师长寿插画家的数据，如今一名不吸烟且健康状况良好的 65 岁女性有 54% 的机会活到 90 岁，31% 的机会活到 95 岁，13% 的机会活到 100 岁。</p><p>新泽西州自由角的财富顾问沃尔特·帕尔多（Walter Pardo）表示，一些退休人员认为自己可以更好地投资这些钱。他说，关键是，你正在将市场风险转移给保险公司。固定收益保障的安全性使您可以更积极地将其他资产投资于罗斯 IRA 或应税账户，从而有可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-inherit-ira-taxes-d6ee70d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为您的继承人留下免税遗产</a>。</p><p>帕尔多说，如果您身体健康，并且在退休之初不需要所有所需的分配，那么 QLAC 可能是一个不错的选择，特别是对于女性而言。</p><p> “那些说‘我可以把这 20 万美元投入谷歌’的人，并没有看到这将为生活提供的现金流的价值，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Ashlea Ebeling： <a href="mailto:ashlea.ebeling@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ashlea.ebeling@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b28e0b44-8140-466a-922c-df1aa6d8aa70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 04:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-break-qlac-annuity-contract-ee88fe4c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-tax-break-qlac-annuity-contract-ee88fe4c<author><![CDATA[Ashlea Ebeling]]></author><category>照片-illo</category><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>保险</category><category>人寿保险</category><category>年金</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>保险</category><category>人寿保险</category><category>年金</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[This Tech Will Help Find Your Next Hike—and Can Save Your Life]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>探索新路线、下载地图以离线访问，并且不要忘记电池组<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070939"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="648" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820825?width=860&amp;height=648" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nicole 与 Strava 的路线建设者计划前往西班牙巴尔德莫萨徒步旅行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：威尔·马夸特</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070939"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-735934/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nicole-nguyen" itemprop="url" rel="author">妮可·阮</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 23 日上午 12:02（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-tech-will-help-find-your-next-hikeand-can-save-your-life-1e53974"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美好的户外活动就是远离屏幕，但您应该随身携带一些科技产品。这些应用程序和小工具非常适合在荒野中行走。有些甚至可以挽救您的生命。</p><p>根据锻炼追踪应用 Strava 的数据，越野运动的增长速度是其他活动的两倍。一位发言人表示，该应用程序的用户通常会在八月份记录最多的加息次数。</p><p>谷歌和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果</a>最近添加了更多适合徒步旅行的地图功能。四月份，谷歌地图<a href="https://blog.google/products/maps/google-maps-update-national-parks-features/" target="_blank" class="icon none">添加了美国国家公园内的步道信息</a>，例如距离和海拔高度。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-maps-app-popularity-iphone-8e52aec1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Apple 地图</a>将在 iOS 17 中显示类似的数据，iOS 17 现已作为<a href="https://beta.apple.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none">公开测试版</a>发布，并将于今年秋季广泛推出。</p><p> AllTrails、Komoot 和 Strava 等专业智能手机应用程序可以帮助您找到隐藏的瑰宝，并提供比 Apple 或 Google 更详细的路线信息。即使您没有蜂窝网络连接，它们也可以引导您完成每个转弯，精确定位您的位置。</p><p>适合您的应用程序取决于您的技能水平。决定支付高级套餐取决于您需要多少定制服务，以及您是否要去没有手机服务的地方。 I&#39;ve used a combination of AllTrails, Komoot and Strava for years—here&#39;s how their latest features compare and how to prep your gadgets before bringing them into the wild.</p><h3> Blaze your trail</h3><p> These apps are your new guidebook, map and compass all-in-one. You can do basic searches without subscribing. For advanced functionality, such as the ability to download routes offline, you need to pay.</p><h4> For beginners: <a href="https://www.alltrails.com/mobile" target="_blank" class="icon none">AllTrails</a> (free to use; $3 a month for premium)</h4><p> AllTrails is the easiest to use. There are over 400,000 trails worldwide on the platform, and its users actively review routes. The reviews section is helpful for parking tips and understanding if there are areas that aren&#39;t well maintained. You can browse trails free and use the app to follow the route, as long as there&#39;s cell service.</p><p> My favorite premium upgrades include offline maps and wrong-turn alerts, plus compatibility with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-cult-of-garmin-why-athletes-stick-with-these-smartwatches-over-apple-or-samsung-11667088984?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Garmin GPS watches</a> . You can also get info for weather and mosquito activity. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f9013f33-0508-4a2d-8268-381269974282.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h4> Intermediate: <a href="https://www.komoot.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Komoot</a> (free to use; one-time map fees cost $4 to $30; $60 a year for premium)</h4><p> Komoot has many similar features: a large database of routes and offline maps. I find the trail search on Komoot less intuitive than AllTrails, and the app doesn&#39;t feature reviews. Its strength is the ability to reroute or add new waypoints on the fly.</p><p> The pricing structure is a little confusing but you get a lot of features by just paying a one-time fee, rather than a recurring subscription. You get one region (essentially a city) free, so pick carefully. You have to pay either $4 per additional region or $30 for the world. Once you unlock regions, you get offline maps and turn-by-turn voice navigation, which is especially useful for cycling. (There is a $60 annual subscription for live tracking and other features, but most people won&#39;t need this.) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a76efafa-9f2d-44a7-a393-f044e10a86cc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h4> Advanced: <a href="https://www.strava.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Strava</a> (free to use; $12 a month for premium)</h4><p> Athlete-geared Strava is much more than a route planner and navigator. It&#39;s part social network, part workout analyzer—and you really need a subscription to plan hikes.<br><br> Strava can suggest hikes, but the app&#39;s route builder is excellent for creating a custom one from scratch. You can pick a start and an end, and the app will survey users&#39; historic data to build an ideal route. The best feature: A <a href="https://www.strava.com/heatmap" target="_blank" class="icon none">global heat map</a> shows which trails are most popular. A less-trafficked line could mean the path isn&#39;t accessible—and should be avoided. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d4f1b392-6906-42ac-8b03-f6342507dd56.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> Prep your tech before you go</h3><p> No matter which app you use, you&#39;ll want to make sure you verify the route, have a plan in case you lose cell service and bring a battery backup.</p><p> <strong>Use multiple sources of information:</strong> “I think that these apps are great to use,” said Lindsey Terrell, a guide for Rare Earth Adventures, a wilderness tour company in Oregon. But, since many trails are crowdsourced, she warned that distance and elevation can be inaccurate. Go to the official website that presides over the hike&#39;s jurisdiction to validate the info, Terrell advised. The National Parks and US Forest Service update their websites with trail and road conditions regularly.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What do you take with you on a hike?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> <strong>Download maps offline:</strong> You may lose service, so make sure you can access your route without it, Terrell said. <a href="https://support.alltrails.com/hc/en-us/articles/360019244771-How-do-I-download-maps-to-my-phone-for-offline-use-" target="_blank" class="icon none">AllTrails</a> , <a href="https://support.komoot.com/hc/en-us/articles/360023078891-Using-komoot-offline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Komoot</a> and <a href="https://support.strava.com/hc/en-us/articles/216917657-Strava-Subscription-Features" target="_blank" class="icon none">Strava</a> require a paid upgrade to view routes without service. I like to download the area <a href="https://support.google.com/maps/answer/6291838?hl=en&amp;co=GENIE.Platform%3DiOS" target="_blank" class="icon none">on Google Maps</a> as a backup. Search for a place, then tap on the address. Tap the three dots icon (top right corner), then select Download offline map. Apple Maps is enabling downloading with iOS 17.</p><p> <strong>Consider a personal locator beacon:</strong> For any hike, you&#39;ll want to let loved ones know which route you&#39;re taking and when they should start worrying, Terrell said.</p><p> If you&#39;re going to a really remote area, Terrell recommends a subscription-based satellite communicator, such as the <a href="https://www.garmin.com/en-US/c/outdoor-recreation/satellite-communicators/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Garmin InReach</a> . <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apples-iphone-14-satellite-emergency-sos-is-live-youll-hopefully-never-use-it-11668517349?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">iPhone 14 models</a> have satellite functionality for contacting emergency services or updating Find My. It works in the US but<a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT213426" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">it isn&#39;t available</a> for all countries. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820947?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> In the fall, an Apple Watch update will let you see where you were last connected to cell service on a remote hike.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苹果</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>A new Apple Watch feature for cellular models—available in the WatchOS 10 now in public beta and expected for all compatible devices in September—shows where you were last connected to your carrier. It can also display when the device last detected <em>any</em> carrier&#39;s network to make an emergency call.</p><p> <strong>Preserve battery life:</strong> GPS tracking can drain your phone&#39;s battery. “Get in the habit of bringing a power bank on every hike,” said Scott Wilkinson, content director for the nonprofit Pacific Crest Trail Association and longtime backpacker. For longer, more remote hikes, he also suggested having a backup GPS device, such as a smartwatch.</p><p> <strong>Protect your device:</strong> “Don&#39;t hike with a naked phone!” Wilkinson urged. If you&#39;re relying on your phone to get you home, save it from damage with a rugged drop-resistant case.</p><p> — <em>For more WSJ Technology analysis, reviews, advice and headlines,</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>sign up for our weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Nicole Nguyen at <a href="mailto:nicole.nguyen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nicole.nguyen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/cdf3741a-b32c-4964-a79a-63023038548a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 04:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-tech-will-help-find-your-next-hikeand-can-save-your-life-1e53974</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-tech-will-help-find-your-next-hikeand-can-save-your-life-1e53974<author><![CDATA[Nicole Nguyen]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category> Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>Computing</category><category> Consumer Electronics</category><category> Electronic Navigation/Tracking Systems</category><category> Satellite Navigation Systems</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category>移动应用软件</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Personal Technology</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>personal technology</category><category> computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>计算</category><category>electronic navigation</category><category> tracking systems</category><category> satellite navigation systems</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category>移动应用软件</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Smart Gadgets That Can Save Your Home—and Your Money]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Detecting water leaks and faulty wiring can protect your family&#39;s biggest investment and your wallet <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820781/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Jason Schneider <span>Illustration by Jason Schneider</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070484"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070484"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-DP318_JARGON_A_20190402105515.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Julie Jargon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 22 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-smart-gadgets-that-can-save-your-homeand-your-money-94780f51"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Is it worth giving up some privacy to make sure your home doesn&#39;t burn to the ground?</p><p> Consumers have been bombarded with smart-home tech in the past decade promising to monitor and protect your biggest asset. Some of these devices, such as smart thermostats, can also help lower your utility bills.</p><p> But the best products for homeowners are ones that check several boxes at once. They safeguard your home and family. They save you money on utilities or insurance premiums. And they lower the chance any future insurance claim would cost you significant money.</p><p> The technology that most often does all of this targets water leaks, house fires and burglaries, say insurers. To do their job, however, these products have to monitor you and your home and collect data.</p><p> “We&#39;ve been in the telematics space with autos for a long time and the adoption of home telematics is now ramping up,” says Randy Termeer, president of property and casualty insurance for USAA, which provides insurance for active-duty military personnel, veterans and their families.</p><p> Insurers largely believe the monitoring is worth it and are providing policyholders with smart gadgets themselves or joining with companies that provide discounted products.</p><p> These companies have been trying to shift toward prevention of damages and away from reacting to them with repairs because prevention is cheaper for insurers and homeowners. And consumer comfort with smart-home tech is helping. The global smart-home market is estimated to be <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/press-releases/2023-02-14/smart-home-automation-market-to-hit-444-98-billion-by-2030-grand-view-research-inc" target="_blank" class="icon none">worth $445 billion</a> by 2030, representing an annual 27% growth rate from now, says business consulting firm Grand View Research.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What smart-home devices do you find most useful?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> related</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/smart-panels-home-improvement-energy-9544da4a?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">New &#39;Smart Panels&#39; Give Homeowners Real-Time Control of Their Energy Use</a></li></ul></div></div><p> Higher insurance premiums due to bad weather and inflation are also spurring adoption. The average cost of homeowners insurance is expected to <a href="https://insurify.com/report/homeowners-insurance/2023-price-projections/" target="_blank" class="icon none">increase by 9% this year</a> , on top of a 7% increase in 2022, according to insurance-comparison firm Insurify. Savings of any kind can offset the rise.</p><p> People who are already using smart-home tech should call their insurance agent to inquire about a discount. Representatives for State Farm and USAA say policyholders can typically use vendors of their choosing but they must provide proof of the tech, such as a certificate from a security-monitoring company.</p><p> Still, using connected devices can mean sharing personal information. For products pitched by an insurance company, be sure to ask what kind of data it will have access to, where your smart-home data will be stored and how it will be used.</p><p> Here&#39;s what to know about the three most money-saving smart-home tech categories:</p><h3> Leak-detection sensors</h3><p> According to Farmers Insurance, <a href="https://www.farmers.com/leak-detection/" target="_blank" class="icon none">water-damage claims</a> are seven times more frequent than claims related to theft or fire. It often starts with a slow drip that can result in mold and costly damage before you even realize there&#39;s a problem. Farmers and other insurers, including <a href="https://www.resideo.com/us/en/corporate/newsroom/all-articles/usaa-accelerates-innovation-and-use-of-emerging-technologies-amid-pandemic/" target="_blank" class="icon none">USAA</a> and <a href="https://www.hippo.com/smart-home" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hippo</a> , offer premium discounts to customers in some states for certain leak-detection devices. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3165d778-e4ea-4b12-867b-b9082f6cee95.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Some sensors alert people on mobile apps if humidity or water is detected near pipes, water heaters, washing machines and refrigerators; other systems can shut off water to the house automatically when a leak is detected.</p><p> USAA sells these different systems directly to customers in most states. In those states, USAA policyholders can buy four connected water sensors for $200, which on average can yield a premium discount of up to 10%.</p><h3> Electrical sensors and fire alarms</h3><p> Another big source of non-weather-related claims are cooking and grease fires, as well as fires caused by faulty wiring. State Farm offers customers in most states an app-paired sensor that plugs into a power outlet and can detect <a href="https://newsroom.statefarm.com/state-farm-offers-customers-more-than-one-million-free-ting-sensors/" target="_blank" class="icon none">electrical power fluctuations</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="793" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820669?width=639&amp;height=793" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> State Farm offers customers a plug-in sensor that can detect electrical power fluctuations that could signal a fire risk.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: State Farm</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Whisker Labs, the company that makes the sensor, provides State Farm aggregate data—not data on individual properties—on power-quality events and any fire hazards the sensor identifies. A State Farm spokesman says the company doesn&#39;t use the data provided by the sensors to determine rates. However, homeowners who don&#39;t rectify known hazards could face rate increases later on.</p><p> Although no premium discount is offered for using the sensor, State Farm offers the device at no cost for three years. A State Farm spokesman says policyholders have reported catching and fixing electrical problems before they resulted in fire.</p><p> Many insurance companies, including <a href="https://www.farmers.com/home/homeowners/discounts/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Farmers</a> and <a href="https://www.allstate.com/resources/home-insurance/home-security-insurance-discounts" target="_blank" class="icon none">Allstate</a> , say homeowners might be eligible to receive discounts for having fire alarms that automatically alert the fire department.</p><h3> Home security systems</h3><p> Many insurers provide discounts for having a home security system, especially if it comes with professional monitoring—meaning a call-center employee calls police if the alarm goes off. State Farm is testing a <a href="https://www.statefarm.com/insurance/home-and-property/homeowners/discounts/adt" target="_blank" class="icon none">partnership with ADT</a> in Illinois, Indiana and Pennsylvania that gives policyholders up to a 6% discount on their premiums. Of course, the premium savings could be lost by the extra money for the ADT monthly fee. USAA works with customers to find competitive rates for security systems.</p><p> People who choose a more DIY route, such as <a href="https://support.ring.com/hc/en-us/articles/360048711732-How-To-Get-a-Professional-Monitoring-Certificate-for-Your-Insurance-Company" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ring doorbell cameras</a> and <a href="https://community.arlo.com/t5/Arlo-Secure/Home-Security-Monitoring-Insurance-Certificate/td-p/1891409" target="_blank" class="icon none">Arlo security cameras</a> , should call to see about discounts, according to State Farm and USAA.</p><h3> Things to consider</h3><p> Anytime something is connected to the internet, there&#39;s a possibility of it being compromised. My colleague Nicole Nguyen explains the privacy considerations of home surveillance systems <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-you-shouldor-shouldntbuy-a-home-security-camera-11659239201" target="_blank" class="icon none">in this column</a> .</p><p> You&#39;ll have to calculate the cost of installing and maintaining your smart-home tech and then compare that to the discount your insurance company offers. Will the investment pay off over time? If not—and if it won&#39;t do much more to keep your family safe—you might skip it.</p><p> <em>—For Family &amp; Tech columns, advice and answers to your most pressing family-related technology questions, sign up for my</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=444&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Julie Jargon at <a href="mailto:Julie.Jargon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Julie.Jargon@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fa51c817-2355-4f0e-b09f-51750ecc0514.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-smart-gadgets-that-can-save-your-homeand-your-money-94780f51</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-smart-gadgets-that-can-save-your-homeand-your-money-94780f51<author><![CDATA[Julie Jargon]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category> Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category> Networking</category><category> Home Networking/Smart Appliances</category><category> Insurance</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category>耐用家居产品</category><category>Consumer Electronics</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>家用电子/电器</category><category>Insurance Technology</category><category> Internet-of-Things Technologies</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Home Improvements</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Personal Technology</category><category> Real Estate/Property</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Home &amp; Garden</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>home improvements</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>personal technology</category><category> real estate</category><category> property</category><category> home &amp; garden</category><category> computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category> networking</category><category> home networking</category><category> smart appliances</category><category> insurance</category><category> consumer goods</category><category>耐用家用产品</