          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821616?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elon Musk has cast his xAI startup as seeking to explore issues that have puzzled humanity for generations.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alain Jocard/AFP/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074580"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tim-higgins" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tim Higgins</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 22, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-tesla-xai-artificial-intelligence-1db53628"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-gets-new-title-of-technoking-of-tesla-11615813693?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">self-proclaimed Technoking</a> sees an AI future and has separate companies pursuing that vision.</p><p> But who wins as the technologies of his companies increasingly overlap?</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> and his kingdom&#39;s tentacles were on prime display this past week, raising questions about whether <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">Tesla</a> investors are helped or hindered by the billionaire&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-xai-artificial-intelligence-company-openai-chatgpt-4a6f178a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">latest startup</a> , xAI. The new venture is taking advantage of the rush of enthusiasm—and presumably money—to develop a humanlike artificial-intelligence technology. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="400" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2124C005-330E-422A-8B3C-AFF22555DE0C&amp;height=400&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;resetOnComplete=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-tesla-xai-artificial-intelligence-1db53628&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Tesla&#39;s earnings call triggered a selloff even though its second-quarter results beat expectations. 《华尔街日报》解释道。 Photo: Samsul Said/Bloomberg<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Meanwhile, many investors have long been excited about Tesla&#39;s work and plans for deploying AI with driverless cars and humanoid robots.</p><p> Tesla isn&#39;t a car company, these investors argue. It is a tech powerhouse that can truly deploy this fuzzy thing called AI into the real world—doing hard, meaningful tasks. And because of that, Musk has even suggested, Tesla is worthy of someday being the world&#39;s most valuable company, more than <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">Apple</a> and Aramco combined. Or, put more simply, a juggernaut worth trillions and trillions of dollars.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “For investors that think that there might be quite a bit of value in the AI features and products of Tesla, it might be concerning to see you pursuing another endeavor where AI is the focus,” William Stein, an analyst focused on AI from Truist Securities, told Musk on Wednesday during the automaker&#39;s quarterly conference call.</p><p> Musk said the companies are complementary. “I think it will actually enhance the value of Tesla,” the chief executive said.</p><p> For years, his array of companies might have helped each other out, but their lanes were pretty clear: Tesla, the only one publicly traded, was for cars; SpaceX, for Mars. Boring Co. was for tunnels; Neuralink, for brain computers. Starlink, a product at SpaceX, was for planetary internet; and Twitter, for interpersonal communications.</p><p> On the surface, the difference between Tesla and xAI so far comes down to the complexity of the problems they want to address. In trying to deploy fully driverless cars, Tesla has been working on a kind of AI traditionally applied narrowly to a specific task: driving.</p><p> In officially rolling out xAI earlier this month, Musk cast his startup as seeking to explore much bigger issues—the sorts of ideas that have puzzled humanity for generations, like, perhaps, the nature of gravity. To do that, he wants to develop an advanced AI—known as artificial general intelligence—with the hope of achieving what sounds like superhuman intelligence. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821626?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla has been working on a kind of AI traditionally applied narrowly to a specific task: driving.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brandon Bell/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Or, as Musk put it, the company&#39;s mission statement is about creating an advanced AI that can answer: “What the hell is really going on?”</p><p> The rub might come down to details, such as xAI&#39;s actual business plan.</p><p> Musk was light on those specifics, beyond saying xAI would compete with OpenAI and Google&#39;s Bard. The success of OpenAI&#39;s generative AI chatbot known as ChatGPT has renewed excitement in Silicon Valley that the more advanced AGI is possible after years of theorizing.</p><p> Still, Musk has painted Tesla as playing an important role in the <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1483728729545363457?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">AGI future</a> , especially as it works to develop a humanoid robot called Optimus, an offshoot of its driverless-car work.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Will increasing focus on AI be a successful strategy for Elon Musk&#39;s empire?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “I think Tesla&#39;s gonna play an important role in AI and AGI, and I think I need to oversee that to make sure it&#39;s good,” Musk told Tesla shareholders in May. “Generally, people do not—or very few people, even in the AI community—do not appreciate just how much capability Tesla has in AI. It&#39;s by far the most advanced real-world AI. There&#39;s no one even close.”</p><p> In 2021, the company held a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-ai-day-2021-11629408749?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">much-hyped AI Day</a> , which included details of work to develop Optimus and computing power specially designed for AI, including a supercomputer dubbed Dojo to help development of its driverless-car technology.</p><p> On Wednesday, Musk revealed for the first time that Tesla is planning to spend more than $1 billion through the end of next year on Dojo, which he said gives the company advantages over rivals looking to train their own driver systems with expensive computing power that is in great demand with the rise of AI companies.</p><p> “I want to say the fundamental rate limiter on the progress of full self-driving is training,” he said. “If we had more training compute, we would get done faster.”</p><p> Tesla&#39;s silicon chip team and maybe its AI software programmers will work with xAI, Musk said earlier this month. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821642?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elon Musk speaking at a test-tunnel unveiling event for Boring Co. in 2018.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Robyn Beck/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Dojo was developed especially to deal with large amounts of video used in making a driverless-car system, and the current version isn&#39;t meant to handle large language models used to create OpenAI-like chatbots. Earlier this month, Musk said the next generation of Dojo will work with such so-called LLMs.</p><p> “Any relationship with Tesla has to be an arm&#39;s-length transaction, because Tesla is a publicly traded company and different shareholder base,” Musk said.</p><p> Navigating how Tesla and xAI might interconnect is something familiar for Musk&#39;s companies.</p><p> For years, regulatory filings have hinted at that interplay, and investors have occasionally complained, including in 2016 when Tesla <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-and-solarcity-agree-to-2-6-billion-merger-deal-1470050724?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">acquired the troubled SolarCity</a> . Musk was then chairman and the largest shareholder of the solar-panel company. A Delaware judge last year ruled that Musk <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-rules-elon-musk-didnt-act-unlawfully-in-solarcity-takeover-11651098103?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">didn&#39;t act unlawfully</a> in the takeover.</p><p> In the early days of his control of Twitter, workers from Tesla and Boring Co. were at the social-media company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-revamps-twitter-with-help-from-tesla-staff-11667510550?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">helping with Musk&#39;s transition</a> . Earlier this year, Tesla disclosed that Twitter had incurred $1.4 million in expenses for “certain commercial and support agreements” between last year and February. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821646?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> SpaceX and Tesla have in recent years worked together by sharing employees.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Joe Skipper/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This past Monday, Sen. Elizabeth Warren, a Democrat from Massachusetts, called on the Securities and Exchange Commission to investigate Tesla regarding disclosures over how it has overseen Musk&#39;s dual role as leader of both Tesla and Twitter that she said has “raised concerns about conflicts of interest, misappropriation of corporate assets, and other negative impacts to Tesla shareholders.”</p><p> In court, Twitter on Thursday told a federal judge it planned to subpoena the senator for communications she has had with the SEC and the Federal Trade Commission. On Twitter, Musk responded with several tweets, including one saying, <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1682143040117301248?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">“Fight fire with fire.”</a></p><p> One of the most notable ways Tesla and SpaceX have worked together in recent years is probably through the sharing of employees, such as a former Apple materials engineering star who now works for the two Musk companies.</p><p> Similarly, the genesis of xAI was to attract talent he couldn&#39;t get at Tesla, Musk said. “There were just some of the world&#39;s best AI engineers and scientists that were willing to join a startup, but they were not willing to join a large, sort of relatively established company like Tesla,” he said.</p><p> Write to Tim Higgins at <a href="mailto:tim.higgins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">tim.higgins@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-tesla-xai-artificial-intelligence-1db53628</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-tesla-xai-artificial-intelligence-1db53628<author><![CDATA[Tim Higgins]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category> Artificial Intelligence Technologies</category><category> Motor Vehicles</category><category> Alternative Fuel Vehicles</category><category> Autonomous Driving Technologies</category><category> Automotive</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Computer Science</category><category> High Net Worth Individuals</category><category> Sciences/Humanities</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Tesla</category><category> TSLA</category><category> Elon Musk</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>artificial intelligence</category><category> machine learning</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>computer science</category><category> high net worth individuals</category><category> sciences</category><category> humanities</category><category> artificial intelligence technologies</category><category> motor vehicles</category><category> alternative fuel vehicles</category><category> autonomous driving technologies</category><category> automotive</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why America’s Largest Tool Company Couldn’t Make a Wrench in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A highly automated Texas factory was supposed to bring the manufacturing of Craftsman mechanics&#39; tools back to American shores. The $90 million project was doomed by equipment problems and slow production. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821631/?width=1000&amp;size=0.8" alt="A Texas-made Craftsman ratchet from Stanley Black &amp; Decker. The company said it was closing the Fort Worth factory 3½ years after breaking ground." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A Texas-made Craftsman ratchet from Stanley Black &amp; Decker. The company said it was closing the Fort Worth factory 3½ years after breaking ground. Evan Jenkins for the Wall Street Journal <span>Evan Jenkins for the Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070397"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070397"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/john-keilman" itemprop="url" rel="author">John Keilman</a></span> | Photographs by Evan Jenkins and <span class="author" itemprop="name">Cooper Neill for The Wall Street Journal</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 22, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The world&#39;s largest tool company couldn&#39;t figure out how to make a wrench.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SWK" class="company-name">Stanley Black &amp; Decker</a> built a $90 million factory on the edge of Fort Worth, Texas, intending to burnish the Made-in-the-USA luster of the Craftsman brand by forging mechanics&#39; tools with unprecedented efficiency. But the automated system was a bust, and the tools that were supposed to be pumped out by the million are so hard to find that some consider them collector&#39;s items.</p><p> In March, 3½ years after breaking ground, Stanley announced it was closing the factory. The property is now being advertised for sale.</p><p> The Craftsman plant was a high-profile example of a drive among US manufacturers to bring offshored plants back home. Government incentives and a desire to shorten supply chains have sparked a factory-building boom. The high cost of American labor makes automation critical for plants to turn a profit.</p><p> Turning manual tasks over to machines, which are supposed to churn out goods with minimal human involvement and maximum productivity, poses its own challenges. The Craftsman factory&#39;s first-of-its-kind system was supposed to make tools so efficiently that costs would be on par with China, but ex-employees said it had problems that couldn&#39;t be fixed before the company decided to pull the plug.</p><p> “It was supposed to be different,” said Tom Felty, who worked in the factory as an electroplating engineer. “It was supposed to be bringing the Craftsman brand back. It was all these new technologies. It&#39;s why I moved from North Carolina to Texas to be a part of it, and it was an absolute disaster.”</p><p> Echoing a previous statement, Stanley blamed several factors for the plant&#39;s closure.</p><p> “We endeavored to make Craftsman mechanics tools in a new and innovative way,” a spokeswoman said. “The events of Covid and supply chain challenges, coupled with technology that did not meet our expectations, resulted in the discontinuation of operations.”</p><p> The company declined to comment further.</p><p> The closure marked a turn for the tool maker, based in New Britain, Conn., which spent much of the past 14 years chasing growth. Stanley merged with Black &amp; Decker in 2010 and bought <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NWL" class="company-name">Newell Brands</a> &#39; tool unit in 2017. The spree turned the company into a colossus, taking it to nearly $17 billion in revenue last year, from $3.7 billion in 2009.</p><p> Craftsman, which accounted for more than $1 billion of that total, was a key part of the expansion. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819957?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Stanley Black &amp; Decker&#39;s now-closed Craftsman factory in Fort Worth, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: cooper neill for the wall street journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For decades, it had been a flagship brand of Sears, which contracted with US manufacturers to make mechanics&#39; tools like wrenches, ratchets and sockets. The tools were fixtures in American homes and garages, but after Sears cut costs by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stanley-to-make-more-craftsman-tools-in-u-s-11557919800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shifting production to China</a> , aficionados said the products&#39; quality declined. Some Craftsman wrenches, for example, fortified their open ends with extra metal, which made them hard to use in tight spaces. That earned them the derisive nickname “lobster claws.”</p><p> Stanley bought Craftsman in 2017 for $900 million, a deal then-Chief Executive James Loree said offered the chance to “re-Americanize” the brand. The company began assembling Craftsman tape measures, air compressors and other products in its US facilities, packaging them with a red, white and blue logo that says “Made in the USA with Global Materials.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821194?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The Fort Worth factory, announced in 2019, was meant to go a step further, forging the brand&#39;s iconic wrenches, ratchets and sockets from American steel to feed a consumer desire for US-made tools. Automation and other advanced manufacturing techniques would allow the plant to compete on cost with imported products, executives said.</p><p> Steve Stafstrom, Stanley&#39;s vice president of global operations at the time, said that required devising a system that would increase both labor and material efficiency far beyond the norm.</p><p> “We had a group of folks very committed to making it work,” he said. “We had to come up with technology that had never been used before.”</p><p> Stanley was already making mechanics&#39; tools for the premium MAC and Proto brands at a factory in nearby Farmers Branch, Texas. Former employees said much of that work was done manually, which is standard for the industry. Workers used tongs to adjust a hot piece of metal as a press smashed it into the shape of a wrench or ratchet, and moved tools by hand from one machine to the next.</p><p> Stanley&#39;s plan for the Craftsman plant centered on automating much of that process, as seen in a YouTube <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZwIPYcZ_yU" target="_blank" class="icon none">video</a> uploaded by a Belarusian company that supplied some of the machinery.</p><p> A bar of steel called a billet was sliced from a coil by a guillotine-like device, then carried by conveyor belt through a heater. A machine rolled the glowing red billet into a shape resembling a lollipop and a robot placed it onto a press, where mechanical fingers moved it through several stations until it was pounded into a fully formed ratchet.</p><p> The video shows piles of unfinished ratchets and wrenches with scarcely any excess metal clinging to them. Ex-workers said the automated method was supposed to increase the yield well above the traditional toolmaking process, in which more than half of a billet&#39;s steel is trimmed away.</p><p> Executives said at Stanley&#39;s May 2019 investor day that the factory would be in production in 18 months. Former employees said that timetable, thrown off by the pandemic, meant the system wasn&#39;t properly tested before being brought up to scale.</p><p> A former operations leader said adjustments to the Belarus-made rolling machine sometimes required new tooling to be sent from overseas, which could take weeks. He and other former employees said wrenches and ratchets became misshapen in the press. One fix would have required running the machine at half capacity, he said, but that would have thrown off the factory&#39;s cost effectiveness. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819954?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Electroplating engineer Tom Felty at his home. &#39;They spent millions of dollars trying to make those machines work,&#39; he says.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: cooper neill for the wall street journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “They spent millions of dollars trying to make those machines work,” said Felty, the electroplating engineer.</p><p> The company in Belarus, AMT Engineering, couldn&#39;t be reached for comment.</p><p> Other parts of the plant had problems, too. Jeremy Scheffer, who worked in heat treating, said sockets sometimes arrived in his section with metal that hadn&#39;t been fully punched out, or without the Craftsman name stamped onto them.</p><p> Stafstrom, who retired in 2021, said the factory&#39;s struggles were exacerbated by attrition among “gray-haired folks” with deep knowledge of tool making, while Felty said turnover at the top of Stanley&#39;s tool division contributed.</p><p> Jeffrey Ansell, the company&#39;s president of global tools and storage when the factory was announced, left that job in 2020 and has since been succeeded by four other executives. He couldn&#39;t be reached for comment.</p><p> Despite the problems, tooling designer Greg Heltne said workers still made thousands of sockets. But retailers didn&#39;t want them without ratchets and wrenches that also had been made in the factory, he and other former workers said.</p><p> “When the customer says, &#39;I want everything I ordered&#39; and we can&#39;t deliver it, there&#39;s not much that can be done,” Heltne said.</p><p> Lowe&#39;s, one of Craftsman&#39;s major retail partners, declined to comment. Other retailers that sell the brand, including Ace Hardware, Amazon.com, Blain&#39;s Farm &amp; Fleet and Atwoods Ranch &amp; Home Goods, didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Former workers said inventory accumulated at the factory. Scheffer said that when top executives and board members visited, he and his colleagues were told to rearrange bins of unfinished sockets so they would be less noticeable.</p><p> “There was a lot of fanfare, a lot of bigwigs checking out the plant,” tooling engineer Ronnie Cotton said. “They were just trying to show some sort of progress, but in the end, it just wasn&#39;t working properly.”</p><p> Rival companies that make mechanics&#39; tools in the US say their factory lines are partially automated but still rely heavily on workers&#39; skills.</p><p> “The artistry of the human being that&#39;s making those wrenches—that matters,” said Wright Tool President Tom Futey, whose company manufactures high-end tools in Barberton, Ohio. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f1a84adb-236f-43cb-9dd5-5a15e3445bea.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Nick Pinchuk, CEO of Snap-on, another premium brand, said that in 2010 the company&#39;s US factories had a roughly 100-to-1 ratio of workers to robots. Today it&#39;s 8 to 1, but the gradual transition helped the company identify the optimal roles for humans and machines, he said.</p><p> “Sometimes the ease of installing automation is a little bit overestimated,” he said. “Where that comes from is, people don&#39;t really understand how the product is made in the first place.”</p><p> Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor and roboticist Julie Shah said people often have expertise and flexibility machines can&#39;t match. She recalled an aerospace company asking whether it could automate the work of an employee who had decades of experience heat-treating components in precise and varied ways.</p><p> “You dig into it and you&#39;re like, &#39;No, that is an extremely computationally complex problem,&#39; ” she said. “It&#39;s really easy to undervalue the judgment and experience that someone brings to what seems to be like a fairly simple task.”</p><p> As tool enthusiasts wondered when Craftsman&#39;s Texas-made products would be available, the company&#39;s social-media accounts offered repeated assurances. In June 2022, Stanley&#39;s Twitter account said the factory was “gearing up for its debut” and aimed to hire another 100 employees.</p><p> By then, Stanley had already announced it was divesting its security business, its oil-and-gas unit and a door-making division in a bid to become a more focused company. An earnings call in July 2022 revealed that the core tool business had suffered a sudden drop in demand after the boom times of the pandemic.</p><p> Stanley&#39;s stock price plummeted and cutbacks became the priority as it tried to whittle down more than $6 billion of inventory. Donald Allan Jr. , who became CEO last year, said the company would reduce its facilities by 30% and the number of products it sells by 40% as it sought to cut $2 billion in costs.</p><p> Some ex-employees said the Craftsman factory seemed to be getting closer to solving its production problems before Stanley began thinning the workforce. Heltne said he and a colleague were laid off this past December.</p><p> The plant, which never reached its planned staffing level of 500 employees, was down to 175 in March when Stanley announced the shutdown. The company said the same day that it was closing a plant in Cheraw, SC, that had 182 employees who made utility knives and portable storage units, folding those operations into other factories. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="1050" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819955?width=700&amp;height=1050" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tooling designer Greg Heltne said he was laid off from the Fort Worth factory this past December.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cooper neill for the wall street journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Cheraw Town Manager Robert Wolfe said a few Stanley workers remain in the plant, and no buyer has materialized. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CWK" class="">Cushman &amp; Wakefield</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the real-estate firm selling the Fort Worth factory, said no deal has closed on that property.</p><p> Craftsman mechanics&#39; tools continue to be made in Asia, according to their packaging. Former Stanley employees said those plants have some automation but still rely on manual processing.</p><p> Allan told an investor conference in May that the company has opened new plants in Mexico to serve the North American market, and that Stanley aimed to reduce its manufacturing presence in Asia. He didn&#39;t specify the brands or tool lines that would be included in the shift.</p><p> Goldman Sachs analyst Joe Ritchie said that the shutdown of the Fort Worth plant is a minor issue in Stanley&#39;s overall business. Shoppers likely will take it in stride if the tools continue to be made overseas, he said, and investors are focused on the broader cost-reduction plan. Shares are up about 27% since the start of the year.</p><p> Some consumers, though, were infuriated. Jeff King, a former tech executive who hosts a YouTube review show called the Den of Tools, said his viewers&#39; excitement about once-beloved tools returning to US production curdled into a feeling that they were misled.</p><p> “Other companies didn&#39;t make promises to bring manufacturing back to the US,” he said. “Craftsman did.”</p><p> Stanley had predicted the factory would make 60 million tools annually, but ex-employees said in the weeks after the shutdown that they weren&#39;t sure if anything had made it to store shelves. By summer, though, domestically manufactured Craftsman socket sets began to appear at retailers.</p><p> A Wall Street Journal reporter on Monday bought an 88-piece set straight out of the shipping box at a Lowe&#39;s in suburban Chicago. The bright red case was embossed with stars and stripes, and inside was a cardboard placard that read, “Forged in Texas.” The set cost $89.98, less than half of what some <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/EBAY" class="company-name">eBay</a> vendors were seeking.</p><p> “LIMITED QTY never to be seen again,” wrote a seller who posted an identical set for $189.99.</p><p> Wisconsin carpenter Eric Jacobi got two sets through an online store that serves the military. A spokeswoman for the Army &amp; Air Force Exchange Service said it had acquired 1,200 produced for a retailer that backed out of its purchase.</p><p> Jacobi, who runs a Craftsman fan group on Facebook, said the tools felt sturdier than their Taiwan-made equivalents, though some sockets were overly shallow and not entirely chrome plated.</p><p> Given their imperfect state and apparent scarcity, he worried that using them could damage their value as a collectible, so he heeded an online follower who advised that he lock the tools away.</p><p> “I don&#39;t think I ever will touch these,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> A brief history of the wrench </h4><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="509" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821773?width=700&amp;height=509" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Cut-out&#39; wrenches carry the names of companies whose equipment they were made to service, and are now prized by collectors.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Don Haury</p></figcaption></figure><ul class="articleList"><li> An iron nut found in a Roman archaeological dig suggested that wrenches were being used as early as the first century AD, according to the book “Ancient Carpenters&#39; Tools.”</li><li> Some of the first published images of wrenches appeared in Diderot&#39;s Encyclopedia, published in 1771.</li><li> American workers of the early 19th century made their own crude wrenches by bending a bar of iron. Blacksmiths forged other versions until commercial production took over in the mid-19th century.</li><li> Farm-equipment manufacturers made customized wrenches to service their machines, said Don Haury, who owns more than 10,000 of the tools.</li><li> During World War II, propaganda artists used the wrench as a symbol of America&#39;s manufacturing might.</li><li> The once-freewheeling design of wrenches has coalesced into metric and fractional sizes. That standardization of wrench sizes didn&#39;t happen in the US until 1929, Haury said. </li></ul><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="518" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821765?width=700&amp;height=518" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Wrenches figured prominently in some World War II propaganda posters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Corbis/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div></div><p> Write to John Keilman at <a href="mailto:john.keilman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">john.keilman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f<author><![CDATA[John Keilman]]></author><category>世杰交易所</category><category>photo-commission</category><category> wsjcorp</category><category> leder</category><category> exchangecover</category><category> Metal Products</category><category> Cutlery/Hand Tools</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category>耐用家居产品</category><category>Houseware</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>Automation</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Stanley Black &amp; Decker</category><category> SWK</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>automation</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>metal products</category><category> cutlery</category><category> hand tools</category><category> consumer goods</category><category>耐用家用产品</category><category>houseware</category><category> industrial goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Biden Goes All In on Bidenomics. Voters Aren’t Buying It.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> High prices have turned economic issues that could&#39;ve been a re-election tailwind into a headwind <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821615/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="President Biden delivers a speech at Philly Shipyard in Philadelphia on Thursday, part of a campaign to get voters more optimistic about the economy." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> President Biden delivers a speech at Philly Shipyard in Philadelphia on Thursday, part of a campaign to get voters more optimistic about the economy. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074136"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074136"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sabrina-siddiqui" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sabrina Siddiqui</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christian-robles" itemprop="url" rel="author">Christian Robles</a></span> | Photographs by Kriston Jae Bethel for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 22, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-goes-all-in-on-bidenomics-voters-arent-buying-it-102be20a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> PHILADELPHIA—President Biden stood at the lectern of a shipyard here with a familiar pitch as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whos-running-for-president-in-2024-adb754e2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">he seeks a second White House term</a> : The economy remains strong.</p><p> “It&#39;s not an accident, it&#39;s my economic plan in action,” Biden told a crowd of mostly union workers Thursday at the latest stop on his nationwide record-burnishing tour. “Together, we&#39;re transforming the country.”</p><p> But many voters aren&#39;t buying it. They say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-in-a-race-to-reverse-voters-pessimism-about-economy-3037b1f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">they haven&#39;t felt the impact</a> of legislation that&#39;s the centerpiece of Biden&#39;s campaign, and they cite what may be his main albatross—inflation. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/inflation-tracker-cpi-data-prices-11657717467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">High prices</a> have turned economic issues that could&#39;ve been a tailwind for his re-election into a headwind.</p><p> “Inflation&#39;s terrible. Everything&#39;s more expensive than it was,” said James Watson, 31 years old, an independent voter who manages a convenience store at a Philadelphia gas station. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822206?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Watson said he opposed former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , who is leading polls for the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-republican-gop-debate-who-7f128142" target="_blank" class="icon none">Republican presidential nomination</a> , over his inflammatory comments on race and allegations of sexual assault. But he is likely to vote for a third-party candidate next year, as he did in 2020, because he&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-biden-age-president-health-f50e14b8" target="_blank" class="icon none">concerned about Biden&#39;s age</a> and feels conditions in the country haven&#39;t substantially improved since the 80-year-old took office.</p><p> That hesitation about Biden&#39;s age and record explains why the incumbent is essentially tied in most polls with Trump, who remains unpopular and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-aileen-cannon-sets-may-2024-trial-date-for-trumps-documents-trial-eefddbae" target="_blank" class="icon none">faces multiple criminal indictments</a> , and why some Democrats worry a third-party ticket could attract enough swing votes to tip the election to the GOP.</p><p> Recent polls also show a disconnect between a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/june-jobs-report-unemployment-rate-economy-growth-2023-af4d6547" target="_blank" class="icon none">buoyant labor market</a> , which added 1.67 million jobs this year through June, and how voters feel about the economy. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-spending-personal-income-april-2023-b1b57c31" target="_blank" class="icon none">Robust consumer spending</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1" target="_blank" class="icon none">inflation declining</a> from a peak of 9.1% in June 2022 to 3% a year later and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-prices-rose-in-march-for-second-straight-month-dbc1553a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">stabilizing housing market</a> have done little to move public perception on an issue that often ranks as a top priority for Americans at the ballot box. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821627?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Guests gather at the Philly Shipyard in Philadelphia before a speech by Biden on Thursday.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A Monmouth University poll released Wednesday showed only three in 10 Americans feel the country is doing a better job recovering economically than the rest of the world since the Covid-19 pandemic. Respondents were split on Biden&#39;s handling of jobs and unemployment, with 47% approving and 48% disapproving of his performance.</p><p> Many other surveys have also found voters giving Biden low marks on the economy. A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/another-biden-trump-presidential-race-in-2024-looks-more-likely-19d88039?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Wall Street Journal poll in April</a> found more people disapproved than approved of his handling of infrastructure by 3 points. Among those who were undecided in a hypothetical match between Biden and Trump, only 10% approved of Biden&#39;s job performance on infrastructure whereas 70% disapproved. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/82c9c5a6-f1ca-4642-bbba-05587a01d585.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Christopher Brown, who works on the warehouse-management system at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NO/XOSL/PHLY" class="company-name">Philly Shipyard</a> where Biden spoke Thursday, is a registered Republican but voted for Biden in 2020 and Hillary Clinton</p> in 2016. This time around, the 34-year-old isn&#39;t committed to supporting Biden again, in part because he believes the president&#39;s economic record is mixed.<p></p><p> “I feel like I&#39;m actually worse off today than I was two years ago, because of the inflation, because of the extra demand,” said Brown, who lives in Willow Grove, Pa.</p><p> While Brown doesn&#39;t blame Biden entirely for inflation, he believes some of the president&#39;s policies have fueled price increases and feels burdened by the cost of his home, groceries and gasoline even though inflation has cooled in the past year. Brown does appreciate Biden&#39;s investment in green energy, including offshore wind farms the president championed on Thursday. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821617?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Christopher Brown, a registered Republican, voted for Biden in 2020 but isn&#39;t committed to supporting him again. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/ae20c5a0-8e08-4d6f-b118-8478eb40ee95.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In recent months, Biden has traveled to Ohio to promote a $1 billion project to restore the Great Lakes and funding to rehabilitate a bridge for commuters and freight between the state and Kentucky. He has highlighted federal investments toward an airport expansion in Boston, the Metro subway in Los Angeles and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-biden-touts-funding-for-rail-tunnels-under-hudson-river-and-in-baltimore-11675186134?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">rail tunnel underneath the Hudson River</a> . And Biden has repeatedly traveled to Pennsylvania, a state that was critical to his 2020 victory over Trump, to discuss water repairs and fixes to the damaged Interstate 95.</p><p> “President Biden and Vice President Harris are proud to run on a record that has lowered prescription drug costs for seniors, brought hundreds of thousands of manufacturing jobs back to the United States, and makes the wealthy pay their fair share,” Biden campaign spokesman TJ Ducklo said. “Like he did in 2020, President Biden looks forward to earning every vote making the case for his economic agenda.”</p><p> Biden&#39;s aides, who often voice frustration in private that the president doesn&#39;t get more credit for the economic gains under his watch, say they are aware of voters&#39; skepticism. The White House has leaned into the phrase <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidenomics-and-its-contradictions-4d76ee7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“Bidenomics”</a> in an effort to showcase how the president&#39;s policies have benefited the middle class, and officials underscore that his legislative achievements poll well with the public.</p><p> Biden&#39;s supporters say they expect more voters to pay closer attention as the race heats up. As the president picks up the pace of his campaign travel and floods the airwaves with advertisements highlighting the implementation of his policies, his support will increase, they added.</p><p> Michael Gillmer, 35, is a registered Republican who voted for Biden over Trump in 2020 and is leaning toward voting for Biden again. Gillmer, a portfolio manager in the financial-services industry, said the Republican Party had moved too far to the right on social issues and credited Biden&#39;s policies with creating jobs in North Carolina, where Gillmer is based.</p><p> Biden traveled to the state in March to tour the Durham-based company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WOLF" class="">Wolfspeed</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> which had announced a $5 billion investment in semiconductor manufacturing that will create an estimated 1,800 jobs. It plans to seek federal funding from the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chips-act-is-bounty-for-semiconductor-companieswith-many-strings-attached-6e72fd67?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chips and Science Act</a> that Biden signed to help underwrite the costs of its expansion. <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821623?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Biden and Saria Gwin-Maye, a member of Ironworkers Local 44, in January after he was introduced to speak near the Brent Spence Bridge in Covington, Ky.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Patrick Semansky/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Despite the project, Gillmer said many undecided voters in his community don&#39;t believe Biden is responsible for such achievements.</p><p> “I think he should get credit, but he doesn&#39;t,” Gillmer said, while adding that younger Democratic politicians, such as Transportation Secretary Pete Buttigieg, may have more impact on the trail.</p><p> “I think the way he can get the biggest clout is to have people campaign who are not him,” Gillmer said.</p><p> Nearly 35,000 projects have been awarded funding under Biden&#39;s infrastructure law, according to the White House. But while money has been quickly disbursed, many projects may take years to complete and potentially carry over into a future administration.</p><p> “It&#39;s just so abstract when you think about it on the orders of magnitude of the federal government,” said Rep. Chrissy Houlahan (D., Pa.), who added that people in her district were starting to see orange cones go up for projects funded by the infrastructure law. “There is a certain amount of time that it will take to unfold, but I think that that will happen over the next, let&#39;s call it, six or seven months.”</p><p> Anastasia Stefek, 31, an immigrant from Russia who will vote in Georgia for her first presidential election, wishes that Biden did more to protect the environment. She isn&#39;t happy that oil production is expanding under the Biden administration and is unclear about the specific ways in which the president has invested in clean-energy technologies. To her, the specifics matter. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821614?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Biden is given a tour of Philly Shipyard, which makes ships for the US Merchant Marine fleet and will make a new, purpose-built ship to install offshore wind turbines.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “So far it&#39;s a lot of talk, not a lot of things being passed,” said Stefek, who plans to vote for a more progressive third-party candidate. She&#39;s not sure if Biden can do anything to win her over.</p><p> Biden&#39;s backers point out that core Democratic voters will be more motivated to turn out for him if he faces a rematch with Trump.</p><p> “I don&#39;t believe my mental health can stand up to another Trump term,” said Alvin Collins, a 48-year-old accountant in Chester Springs, Pa.</p><p> Collins <strong>,</strong> a Democrat who voted for Biden in 2020, said he supports <strong>&nbsp;</strong> the president&#39;s policies, although they have yet to benefit him directly, and he would prefer a candidate who was “a little more energetic.” But he believes that Trump and Republicans are more focused on stoking divisions and that the country is in more stable hands with Biden.</p><p> “There&#39;s more leadership,” he said. “There&#39;s just a lack of chaos.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How should President Biden frame his accomplishments on the campaign trail?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Write to Sabrina Siddiqui at <a href="mailto:sabrina.siddiqui@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sabrina.siddiqui@wsj.com</a> and Christian Robles at <a href="mailto:christian.robles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christian.robles@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-goes-all-in-on-bidenomics-voters-arent-buying-it-102be20a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-goes-all-in-on-bidenomics-voters-arent-buying-it-102be20a<author><![CDATA[Sabrina SiddiquiChristian Robles]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>National/Presidential Elections</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Biden</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>presidential elections </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The 30% Rule and Other Things I Wish I Knew Before Starting My Home Renovation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Take it from someone who&#39;s been there: It&#39;s not all pretty wallpaper and paint swatches. Sometimes the only way to learn the hard lessons of home remodeling is to live it. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036349"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816897?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> HOME FRIED Salvaged pieces like this marble mantel can look great but be tricky to install, frustrating inexperienced contractors and running up costs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rachel Kuzma/Corcoran </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036349"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-karnasiewicz" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sarah Karnasiewicz</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 22, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-i-wish-i-knew-before-starting-my-home-renovation-93d8d379"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <strong>SOME KIDS</strong> collect baseball cards. Me? By age 13, I was blowing my allowance on Bakelite flatware and Art Deco dressing tables.</p><p> So when, 12 years ago, my husband and I bought a 140-year-old fixer-upper in Gowanus, Brooklyn, and embarked on a soup-to-nuts renovation, it seemed thrillingly inevitable. I&#39;d watched all the shows, read all the magazines and thought I knew the rules—get multiple bids, pad your bottom line and don&#39;t forget to send presents to the neighbors.可能会出什么问题？</p><p> The answer, of course, was just about everything. Subcontractors defected, architects dropped dead (yes, you read that right), budgets ballooned, appliances busted. In the end, the project took 16 months—and what felt like 16 years off my life. But the upshot was a stylish home and a new perspective on what it takes to do the job right. (Evidence: Eight years later, we moved and did it all over again—with fewer, or at least different, mistakes.)</p><p> Toying with taking the plunge yourself? Here, care of my hard-won wisdom and that of industry vets, a few lessons to keep in mind before even reaching for a paint sample.</p><h3> 1. One recommendation isn&#39;t enough.</h3><p> You wouldn&#39;t marry someone on the basis of a single good date. Well, for the duration of a renovation, consider your general contractor your spouse.</p><p> When I met my GC, he&#39;d just wrapped a job for an architect friend with an exacting temperament—all of which seemed auspicious. But months into our project, he stopped paying his subs—a nightmare that never came up with my pal.</p><p> “Unfortunately, a lot can change within a year in a business,” said Carol Wang, a realtor in Brooklyn, NY, who&#39;s currently fixing up her own two-family home. To protect yourself from conflict, delays and liens, check multiple references, time payments to reflect appreciable progress and always ask subcontractors for receipts. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816896?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An &#39;after&#39; view of the author&#39;s first home renovation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rachel Kuzma/Corcoran</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> 2. It&#39;s not just milk that&#39;s gotten more expensive.</h3><p> Maybe you got a good deal on custom carpentry a few years ago; don&#39;t count on the same luck today. “I&#39;m seeing renos that were $600,000 in 2019 coming in with bids three times that,” said Wang. “One designer told me she assumes 8% to 11% inflation in every project.”</p><p> Bottom line: The old advice to budget 10% to 15% for unforeseen overages is hopelessly outdated. Think 25% to 30% instead.</p><h3> 3. Begin with the not-so-fun stuff.</h3><p> It&#39;s thrilling to order block-printed wallpaper and hand-glazed Moroccan tile, but blingy finishes are only as good as the structures they cover.</p><p> “Boilers, plumbing, wiring—that&#39;s where you say &#39;I just spent $17,000 and everything looks the same&#39;—but the underpinnings are everything,” said Kelli Suozzo of Bowerbird Design in Red Bank, NJ Don&#39;t want to run out of money for the sexy stuff—or, you know, furniture? “Make sure you&#39;ve covered the boring things first.”</p><h3> 4. Make a list of must-haves—and check it (more than) twice.</h3><p> When social worker Sara Goodliss started renovating her Dover, Mass., home a few years ago, she was adamant about one thing: heated bathroom floors. “But in the fog of nine million decisions, I forgot to remind the contractor that they were a priority—until all the tile was down and I realized it had never been executed,” she moaned. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a37878ea-4cc8-406d-8930-fc21d6dff411.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> 5. That cool old piece? It&#39;s going to be a hassle.</h3><p> Antique house parts might look killer—but chances are they&#39;ll take three times as long to install (and therefore cost you a pretty penny in labor) and depending on the skill of your crew, always look a little janky. I know because—from a marble mantel salvaged from a Gloucester, Mass., sea captain&#39;s house to Edwardian-era doorknobs—I bought almost nothing new for my first house. Which is why my bathroom doors never closed completely.</p><h3> 6. Plan for the long haul.</h3><p> Don&#39;t underestimate the exhaustion—both physical and decision fatigue—that long-term disruption to your home can cause. Around month 10 of our first project—when my husband worked nights and my 1-year-old son and I were sleeping in a closet—I came down with a raging case of stress-induced shingles.</p><p> Philadelphia interior designer Michelle Gage cites her own marathon renovation as a cautionary tale. “Clients sign up for the dream, but living through years of work is way different than scrolling &#39;after&#39; shots on Instagram,” she said.</p><p> The best defense? Get all your design decisions out of the way upfront—preferably with a professional who can manage when your energy for minutiae inevitably flags. (Designers are pricey—but so is divorce.) Also: Devise a long-range calendar with your partner that includes travel, holidays, even date nights. “Make it part of your whole life or you will burn out,” said Gage. “I know because I did.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What lessons have you learned from undertaking home renovations?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> MORE IN DESIGN &amp; DECORATING</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-to-make-your-bed-the-five-star-hotel-way-e5994c80?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">How to Make Your Bed the Five-Star-Hotel Way</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/quiz-how-controlling-are-you-when-it-comes-to-your-kids-bedroom-decor-9e3980dc?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Quiz: How Controlling Are You When It Comes to Your Kids&#39; Bedroom Decor?</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-downsizing-inspires-creativity-im-73-i-can-do-whatever-the-hell-i-want-6e4114a8?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">When Downsizing Inspires Creativity: &#39;I&#39;m 73. I Can Do Whatever the Hell I Want.&#39;</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-apartment-memories-the-challenges-and-joys-of-decorating-when-youre-penniless-fcfaebf6?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">First Apartment Memories: The Challenges and Joys of Decorating When You&#39;re Penniless</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-parents-want-to-pass-down-furniture-you-hate-6624610?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">When Parents Want to Pass Down Furniture You Hate: An Awkward True Story</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-i-wish-i-knew-before-starting-my-home-renovation-93d8d379</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-i-wish-i-knew-before-starting-my-home-renovation-93d8d379<author><![CDATA[Sarah Karnasiewicz]]></author><category> off duty</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Exotic New Silicon-Based Speakers Are Coming to Next-Generation Earbuds]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>星号大小的扬声器有可能改变我们再现声音的方式、应对听力损失，甚至使虚拟现实中的物体感觉真实<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820867/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="USound 的微型硅基 MEMS 扬声器。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> USound 的微型硅基 MEMS 扬声器。美声<span>美声</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073576"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073576"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christopher-mims"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://si.wsj.net/public/resources/images/BN-CW279_mims_A_20140520065912.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christopher-mims" itemprop="url" rel="author">克里斯托弗·米姆斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/exotic-new-silicon-based-speakers-are-coming-to-next-generation-earbuds-ee99b76b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>人类再现录制声音的方式在未来十年可能会比上个世纪发生更大的变化。</p><p>即将推出的是固态扬声器，由超纯硅晶圆（如微芯片）蚀刻而成。这意味着它们的运行方式与当今任何产品都一样，而且它们具有现有声音再现系统无法比拟的功能。</p><p>这项技术还体现了一个更广泛的趋势——将所有电子元件转换为固态硅——这很容易被认为是理所当然的，但对我们与世界互动的方式产生了深远的影响。</p><p>长期以来，声音制作一直是迈向固态一切的阻碍。虽然扬声器相对保持不变，但我们手机中的几乎所有组件，从传感器到允许无线连接的天线， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-nanotechnology-revolution-is-herewe-just-havent-noticed-yet-11642827640?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">现在都是由数十亿个相同的技术和大多数相同的材料制成的，用于制造微芯片</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="901" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820872?width=700&amp;height=901" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> USound 的一款 MEMS 扬声器的分解图。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国声音</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>使这一转变成为可能的技术被称为 MEMS（微机电系统的缩写），这就是为什么 20 世纪 90 年代 RadioShack 的所有设备都可以塞进现在可以装在我们口袋里的纤薄触摸感应玻璃板中。</p><p>到目前为止，在扬声器领域，只有少数产品采用了 MEMS 技术。我尝试过一种产品——音频工程师使用的那种原型入耳式监听器——并且对其性能印象深刻。</p><p>跟踪音频技术行业的 SAR Insight &amp; Consulting 创始人 Peter Cooney 十年来一直关注基于 MEMS 或固态扬声器的世界。他说，今年和明年，它们最终将成为普通消费者可能购买的设备，例如高端无线耳机。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多关键词</h4><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-how-twitter-could-become-irrelevant-b2b027af?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Twitter 可能会变得无关紧要</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-jobs-replace-tech-workers-8f3dc92?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能会给你的工作带来什么？看看它已经对程序员做了什么</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pandemic-habits-shopping-restaurants-delivery-exercise-payments-a2dba53e?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这些大流行时代的习惯不会消失</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-gm-ford-biden-administration-ev-charging-5914f547?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为什么美国还没有准备好接受电动汽车的接管</a></li></ul></div></div><p>xMEMS 是一家开发这项技术的公司，该公司发言人表示，该公司已向数十家公司提供了其扬声器原型，其中 30 多家公司正在开发基于该技术的耳塞和其他产品。</p><p>布莱恩·卢西 (Brian Lucey) 是入耳式监听器原型的接受者之一，这种监听器是专业人士在掌握音乐曲目时使用的高保真耳塞。 Lucey 是九位格莱美奖获得者的母带工程师，他告诉我，他使用的入耳式监听器中的固态扬声器已经变得不可或缺。</p><p>但最终，这项技术可能无处不在——在每部智能手机中，以及几乎所有耳塞、智能眼镜和即将上市的各种其他“耳戴式设备”中。事实上，我们有理由相信这些固态扬声器在不久的将来可能会来自一个熟悉的品牌。中国的 Luxshare 是致力于将其集成到消费设备中的制造商之一，该公司生产<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>AirPods <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-is-breaking-its-own-rules-with-a-new-headset-80c9b36c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">以及新款 Vision Pro 耳机</a>。</p><p>立讯精密和苹果没有回应置评请求。</p><h3><strong>从亚历山大·格雷厄姆·贝尔到纳米级制造</strong></h3><p>大多数扬声器内发声的部件（无论是连接到立体声音响的扬声器还是耳机内的扬声器）几乎都遵循相同的原理。 1876 年，亚历山大·格雷厄姆·贝尔 (Alexander Graham Bell) 在为第一部电话设计的扬声器中引入了这一想法的第一个可行示例。 （如果你想对此大惊小怪的话——我知道读这篇文章的发烧友会——这是这个想法的改进版本，由 Magnavox 的创始人在 1900 年代初提出，这是当今扬声器最直接的前身。） </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820880?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> XMEMS 的微型扬声器模块。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：xMEMS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://edisontechcenter.org/speakers.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">它的工作原理是这样的</a>：扬声器内部有一块磁铁，里面有一个线圈，线圈连接到坚硬但柔韧的薄膜上——如果您从扬声器箱体前面取下格栅，您就会看到这种薄膜。穿过电线的电流脉冲转化为振动，膜将振动转化为空气的运动，我们称之为声音。</p><p>自发明以来，工程师们对这种设计进行了无数次改进，但没有从根本上改变它。这些改进就是今天的扬声器可以安装到智能手机或助听器中的原因。</p><p>基于 MEMS 的扬声器将所有这些部件整合到一个单元中。因此，它可以更小，同时提供更高的清晰度，并且可能需要更少的功率。这些扬声器采用了一种已在基于 MEMS 的设备中广泛采用的原理，即压电原理。</p><p>当你给压电物质通电时，它们就会移动。其中一些移动速度相当快。例如，手机中微小的梳状天线每秒振动数十亿次。这些物质可以由硅制成，并在顶部添加一层压电材料薄膜。</p><p>总部位于奥地利的 USound 与总部位于加利福尼亚州圣克拉拉的 xMEMS 似乎在将这项技术推向市场方面处于领先地位，该公司生产的固态扬声器使用硅顶部分层的少量压电材料来移动附着在薄膜上的活塞，<a href="https://usound.com/how-do-usound-mems-speakers-work/" target="_blank" class="icon none">从而产生声音</a>。在某种程度上，USound 的工程师就好像用一块硅代替了典型扬声器中的线圈和磁铁。</p><p> xMEMS 的工程师更进一步——他们的整个扬声器，包括振动膜，都是在超纯硅晶圆上制成的——与制造世界上几乎所有计算设备“大脑”的所有微芯片所用的硅晶圆相同。</p><p>成立于 2014 年的 USound 首席技术官 Andrea Rusconi Clerici 表示，基于 MEMS 的扬声器厚度可能只有 1 毫米，是智能手机和耳塞等设备中通常使用的最小扬声器厚度的四分之一。USound 已经在市场上推出了至少一款产品：一副配备 MEMS 扬声器的眼镜。 USound 的最新扬声器长 5 毫米，宽 1.4 毫米，大约相当于印刷书籍中星号的大小。</p><h3><strong>音乐就像你记得的那样</strong></h3><p>Cooney 表示，这项技术最大的应用是无线耳机市场，该市场每年约 4 亿对。这些耳机的价格范围从 Temu 上售价 20 美元的耳机到 Bose 和 Apple 等公司售价 300 美元的耳机不等。</p><p>当然，为了获得吸引力，该技术实际上必须提供当今传统耳塞所无法提供的功能。</p><p>所以我自己尝试了一下。我的体验的简短版本是，虽然当今最好的耳塞（例如 AirPods Pro 2）非常擅长提供温暖的声音和清晰的通话，但我们都遗漏了相当多的东西，这也是在家聆听（即使使用最好的设备）仍然无法与现场音乐相比的部分原因。</p><p>我惊讶地发现，在固态耳塞上尝试一些最喜欢的曲目时，会暴露出我以前没有注意到的细节，甚至是乐器，而且即使使用高端传统入耳式耳机，我也无法识别出这些细节。我可能会在家里使用带有独特低音扬声器和高音扬声器的昂贵扬声器获得类似的体验，但这项技术的重点在于它可以装在你的口袋里，可以带到任何地方。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820878?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">这块8英寸的硅片上包含了数百个微型扬声器。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：xMEM</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>母带处理工程师 Lucey 表示，固态扬声器能够发出更清晰声音的部分原因是微小的压电硅片可以更快速、更精确地移动。 “理想情况下，一个完美的扬声器在你让它走时就会走动，当你说停止时它就会停止移动，而这在很多方面都更接近理想状态，”他补充道。</p><h3>硅基音频的可能未来</h3><p>如果音频行业的主要参与者确实采用固态扬声器，那么这种转变可能需要数年甚至数十年的时间。这些类型的扬声器可能永远与传统扬声器搭配使用，而传统扬声器目前在产生低音方面要好得多。</p><p>产生低频声音不仅对于帮助人们感受节奏至关重要，而且对于当今耳塞的降噪能力也至关重要。这可能意味着未来的耳机将拥有独立的驱动器——一个传统驱动器，一个固态驱动器。</p><p>但耳塞式耳机以及后来的耳罩式耳机只是这些设备的开始。</p><p>一旦用硅制造机械物体，它就能找到各种意想不到的新应用。例如，第一个惯性测量单元——用于确定物体的运动和方向——是为阿波罗飞船创建的，有篮球那么大。它的固态版本只有一粒沙子大小，这就是你的手机知道你何时在纵向和横向模式之间切换的原因。 （这也是智能手表能够识别您何时锻炼的原因。​​）</p><p>目前，固态扬声器的一项奇特但具有潜在变革性的应用仍处于原型阶段，它正在使仅存在于增强现实和虚拟现实中的物体感觉真实。事实证明，通过使用微型扬声器阵列，可以产生对人手施加力的超声波场。例如，这可以模拟两个人在 VR 中握手，或者模拟虚拟物体的感觉。</p><p>库尼说，另一个潜在的应用（目前还很遥远）是为听力损失者设计的植入式扬声器。与此同时，FDA 最近做出的改变使得公司可以销售<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cheaper-over-the-counter-hearing-aids-are-coming-heres-how-to-comparison-shop-11660955368" target="_blank" class="icon none">非处方助听器</a>。由于固态扬声器擅长产生首先出现听力损失的较高频率，因此它们可能是这种应用的理想选择。</p><p>苹果公司不销售非处方助听器。但它的 AirPods Pro 已经可以作为一对使用， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/airpods-pro-amplify-speech-as-well-as-some-hearing-aids-11668531282" target="_blank" class="icon none">适合轻度至中度听力损失的人</a>。无论苹果未来是否使用基于 MEMS 的扬声器来增强这一功能，其竞争对手之一都可能会尝试。</p><p><em>欲了解更多《华尔街日报》技术分析、评论、建议和头条新闻，</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>请订阅我们的每周通讯</em></a><em>。</em></p><p>写信给克里斯托弗·米姆斯 (Christopher Mims)： <a href="mailto:christopher.mims@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christopher.mims@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/exotic-new-silicon-based-speakers-are-coming-to-next- Generation-earbuds-ee99b76b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/exotic-new-silicon-based-speakers-are-coming-to-next- Generation-earbuds-ee99b76b<author><![CDATA[Christopher Mims]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category>技术</category><category>创新</category><category>世杰交易所</category><category>Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category>电子消费品配件</category><category>Consumer Goods</category><category>耐用家居产品</category><category>Consumer Electronics</category><category>家用电子/电器</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟现实技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>技术</category><category>创新</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category>电子消费品配件</category><category>consumer goods</category><category>耐用家用产品</category><category>家用电子产品</category><category>电器</category><category>虚拟现实技术</category></item></channel></rss>